When you push a Django project to a repository (like GitHub), you want to avoid uploading "junk" files, sensitive credentials, or your entire virtual environment.

A .gitignore file tells Git which files to ignore so your repo stays clean and secure. Create a file named .gitignore (start with a dot) in your root project directory (the same level as manage.py) and paste the following:

Plaintext
# Byte-compiled / optimized / DLL files
__pycache__/
*.py[cod]
*$py.class

# Virtual Environment
.env/
.venv/
venv/
env/
ENV/

# Django sensitive files
db.sqlite3
db.sqlite3-journal
local_settings.py
.secrets
.env

# Media and Static
/static/
/media/

# IDEs and Editors
.vscode/
.idea/
*.swp
*.swo

# OS generated files
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db